            AppRoutes = """["/quotes"]""",
            Tags = """["quotes","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body": "## Building a Detailed Cost Estimate\n\nBeyond typing a single price on a line, the quote screen has a **bottom-up estimating tool** that helps you price a part from the shop floor up. You describe how the part is actually made, and it works out a defensible unit price for each quantity you might quote. This tool is still being finished, so for now treat the numbers it produces as a preview, not a firm cost — until it's fully turned on, price your firm quotes from your own known costs.\n\nHere is what the tool captures, and why each piece matters when you quote:\n\n- **Quantity breaks.** Enter the quantities the customer might order — say 10, 50, and 250. The tool prices each one. Setup and one-time charges spread across more parts at higher volumes, so the unit price normally drops as the quantity climbs. Quoting all three lets the customer see the volume discount for themselves.\n- **Margin vs. markup.** You choose how profit is added on top of cost, and the two are not the same thing. **Markup** adds a percentage of your cost (cost plus 30% markup). **Margin** is the share of the selling price that is profit (a 30% margin means cost is 70% of the price). The same percentage gives a higher price under margin than under markup, so be sure you're using the one your shop quotes on.\n- **Labor and machine time per operation.** For each operation (turning, milling, deburr, and so on) you enter the **setup time** charged once per lot, and the **run time** per piece. Setup is spread over the whole lot; run time scales with quantity. Together with your labor and shop overhead (**burden**) rates, this becomes the labor and burden cost.\n- **Scrap allowance.** If an operation loses parts, add a scrap percentage. The tool starts extra pieces so you still ship the ordered quantity, and folds that waste into the price. A 5% scrap rate means you plan to make a few more than ordered.\n- **Material and drop.** Enter how much material each piece uses, its cost, and a **drop** (waste) allowance for the offcut you can't use. Bar ends and sheet remnants are real cost — the drop allowance makes sure the quote covers them.\n- **Outside processing (OSP) / subcontract.** When a step goes to an outside vendor — plating, heat treat, anodize — enter the vendor's per-piece cost and any minimum charge. If the whole part is bought finished from a subcontractor, price it that way instead. Vendor minimums matter most on small lots, where the minimum can dominate the price.\n- **One-time (NRE) charges.** Non-recurring charges — a fixture, a program, first-article inspection — are counted once for the job, not on every piece. The tool keeps them out of the per-piece cost so they don't balloon on large quantities.\n\nFor each quantity break, the tool shows the **cost breakdown** — labor, burden, material, outside processing, and one-time charges — along with the unit price, the extended (line) price, and the resulting **margin**. That margin is the real margin on the price you're quoting, so you can sanity-check that every break still earns what your shop needs before you send it.\n\n## How a Part's Price Fills In\n\nWhen you add a part to a quote line, the price often fills in for you, but where it comes from depends on which screen you're using:\n\n- **In the New Quote window**, the price comes from the part's standard price that was already worked out for this customer. If that customer has no price set for the part, the field is left blank for you to type one in. When a price does fill in, a **LIST** tag appears next to it; change the price yourself and the tag goes away.\n- **On a saved Draft's detail panel**, picking a part looks up the customer's price fresh at that moment. If there's a price on file it fills in; if not, you type one. Picking a part also fills in the description when you've left it blank, so you don't have to retype the part name.\n\nEither way, the filled-in number is only a starting point — you always have the final say on the price you quote.\n\n## Your In-Progress Quote Is Saved\n\nAs you build a new quote, your work is saved automatically behind the scenes — customer, expiration, tax rate, notes, and every line you've added. If your browser reloads or you get pulled away mid-entry, you can pick up where you left off instead of starting over. Once you actually save the quote, that recovery copy is cleared. (This safety net covers the New Quote window; when you edit lines on a saved Draft, each change is stored the moment you make it, so there's nothing to recover.)\n\n## Gotchas Worth Knowing\n\n- **Why Save stays greyed out.** A new quote won't save until you've picked a customer and added at least one line. Hover the greyed button and it tells you what's still missing — most often \"at least one line item is required.\"\n- **Enter tax as a percentage.** Type the tax rate as a plain percentage — `7.25` for 7.25%, not `0.0725`. It's applied to the subtotal to figure the tax.\n- **Free-text lines when editing a Draft.** In the New Quote window every line needs a part. But when you edit lines on a saved Draft, you can leave the part empty and just type a description — handy for a lump-sum or a one-off charge that isn't a catalog part. A description is required there instead.\n- **Tax fills in from the customer's state.** Picking a customer looks up their state's sales-tax rate and fills it in with a tag like \"CA 7.25%\" (or a plain default when the state isn't known). Change it by hand and the tag clears — your entered rate wins.\n\n## Status Colors at a Glance\n\nEach quote wears a colored label so you can read its stage from the list:\n\n- **Draft** — gray. Still yours to edit, send, or delete.\n- **Sent** — blue. It's with the customer; you're waiting on a yes or no.\n- **Accepted** — green. The customer said yes; you can turn it into a sales order.\n- **Declined** — red. The customer passed. End of the road.\n- **Expired** — yellow. It aged past its expiration date without an answer.\n- **Converted to Order** — purple. It became a sales order, with a link to that order.\n\n## Estimate, Quote, and What \"Convert\" Means\n\nTwo different \"convert\" actions live in this area, and it helps to keep them straight:\n\n- **Estimate → Quote.** An **estimate** is a lighter, non-binding ballpark you start on the customer's page. When the customer is ready for real numbers, you promote that estimate into a full, line-itemized **quote**. The quote keeps a link back to the estimate it came from, so you have the whole history from first ballpark to firm price.\n- **Quote → Sales Order.** Once a quote is **Accepted**, converting it hands the parts, quantities, prices, and customer straight to a new sales order — no re-keying — and links the two.\n\nOne thing that trips people up: **the Convert to Order button only shows while the quote can still be converted.** Once you've already converted a quote, that button is gone — its job is done, and the quote now shows a link to the order it produced instead. A quote also won't convert until it's been Accepted, so if you don't see the button on a Sent quote, that's why: get the customer's acceptance first.", "sections": []}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Quotes training modules");
    }
}
